TITLE: Demonstrating Float64 Behavior for JavaScript Numbers
DESCRIPTION: This code demonstrates floating-point behaviors specified by ECMAScript, showing cases where JavaScript operations must produce Float64 results even with integer inputs: precision limits, negative zeros, infinities, and NaN values.
SOURCE: https://github.com/v8/v8.dev/blob/main/src/blog/react-cliff.md#2025-04-10_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
// Float64 has a safe integer range of 53 bits. Beyond that range,
// you must lose precision.
2**53 === 2**53+1;
// â†’ true

// Float64 supports negative zeros, so -1 * 0 must be -0, but
// there's no way to represent negative zero in two's complement.
-1*0 === -0;
// â†’ true

